body: You can reuse the inputs. You don't need to create them every time.

> You can reuse the inputs. You don't need to create them every time.
@snnn thiank for ur quick reply. I have tried it, got error. Told me i was using value before  declaration. I think after Run() method, onnxruntime will free OrtValue. Is there example of this?

It depends on whether the input tensor's shape will change or not , if it is constant, 

See:
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/csharp/test/Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.EndToEndTests.Capi/C_Api_Sample.cpp#L135

IYou may define the OrtValue outside of the loops. And call CreateTensorWithDataAsOrtValue only once. Inside the loop, you just change the pointed memory underneath(input_tensor_values). 

If it is not constant, then you'll have to recreate the OrtValue every time.
@snnn, OK,I got it finally. But its also very slow.  Baseline LPCNet synthesizes 9s audio using only 3s, and onnxruntime need 20s... Y got this result.
Let's do some debugging to find out...
Developer of LPCNet manually optimized operations of GRU with c for inference.  It can explain this result.

@zhuxiaoxuhit, meaning LPCNet infers by GPU while Ort in your case is ony by CPU?
It the difference is reasonable, shall we close the issue?

You need to build ORT using CUDA for it to run using GPU. Comparing CPU perf for this model vs GPU is not valid, and the original lpcnet appears to have a hard dependency on running on GPU (e.g. it imports keras.layers.CuDNNGRU which is only available on GPU).

ALL with CPU. I mean the reason is author of LPCNet did excellent optimization for LPCNet on CPU. He optimized calculations
of Layer Embedding to GRU's  non-recurrent units, this operations are in for loop.  He pre-computed the product
of the embedding matrices with the corresponding submatrices of the GRU’s non-recurrent weights.
OK, I will close this issue. If you optimize this situation in the future, I will try it again.
